Step one — Input image
So everything starts with a raw photograph coming from the CCPD dataset. These images are not clean studio shots. They come from four different conditions — normal base images, blurred images, rotated images, and weather-affected images. So right from the start, the pipeline is dealing with a wide variety of visual quality. The image comes in as a standard BGR format, which is just how OpenCV reads images by default. That's your starting point.

Step two — Grayscale conversion
The first thing the pipeline does is throw away all the color information. And this is actually a deliberate, smart decision. License plates are detected based on their shape, their edges, and their rectangular structure — not their color. Keeping three color channels would just triple the amount of data being processed with no real benefit. So you collapse the BGR image into a single intensity channel. Every pixel goes from being three numbers to being one number representing brightness. The pipeline becomes simpler and faster from this point on.

Step three — Histogram equalization
Now this is where the pipeline tries to deal with the lighting problem. Raw grayscale images from real-world conditions can be very dark, very washed out, or unevenly lit. Histogram equalization looks at the full distribution of pixel intensities across the image and redistributes them so they span the full range from 0 to 255 more evenly. The practical effect is that dark images get brighter, low-contrast regions become more distinguishable, and the plate boundary becomes more visible.
The honest limitation here though is that this is a global operation. It treats the entire image as one uniform region. If part of the image is in shadow and another part is in bright sunlight, equalization averages across both and does a mediocre job on each. A more sophisticated approach would use CLAHE — Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization — which does this locally in small tiles. But the pipeline uses the simpler global version.

Step four — Gaussian blur
Right before edge detection, the pipeline applies a 5x5 Gaussian blur. This might seem counterintuitive — you're about to detect edges, so why make the image softer? The reason is noise. A raw grayscale image has tiny random pixel variations everywhere — sensor noise, compression artifacts, texture inside the license plate characters themselves. If you run edge detection on an unblurred image, Canny fires on all of that noise and you end up with thousands of tiny fragmented edges that have nothing to do with the plate boundary. The Gaussian blur smooths all of that out so that only the strong meaningful edges survive. Think of it as a noise filter specifically designed to prepare the image for the next step.

Step five — Canny edge detection
This is the core of the edge extraction phase. Canny works by computing the intensity gradient at every pixel — essentially asking "how fast is brightness changing here?" At a plate boundary, brightness changes sharply from the plate color to the background. That produces a high gradient value. In flat uniform regions, brightness barely changes, so the gradient is low.
Canny then applies two thresholds — the low and high Canny values that were grid-searched. Any gradient above the high threshold is immediately accepted as a definite edge. Any gradient below the low threshold is immediately rejected. Anything in between is only kept if it's connected to a definite edge. This hysteresis mechanism is what makes Canny much cleaner than a simple threshold — it traces continuous edge contours rather than isolated noisy pixels.
The output is a binary image. White pixels are edges, black pixels are not. At this point you can start to see the outline of a license plate if the conditions are good — but the outline is almost never perfectly closed. There are gaps where characters break the border, where lighting is uneven, where the image is blurred. That's the problem the next step solves.

Step six — Morphological closing
So after Canny you have an edge map full of broken lines and gaps. Morphological closing is specifically designed to connect those gaps. It works in two stages internally — first a dilation which expands all the white edge pixels outward, and then an erosion which shrinks them back. The net effect is that gaps smaller than the kernel get filled in, while the overall shape and size of the edges is preserved.
The kernel here is a wide rectangle — something like 17 pixels wide and 5 pixels tall. That shape is very intentional. License plates are horizontal rectangles, so the gaps you need to bridge are mostly horizontal gaps between characters. A wide horizontal kernel is perfectly shaped to jump across those horizontal gaps. If you used a square kernel, you'd close gaps in all directions equally, which would start merging things that shouldn't be merged.
After this step, what was a broken outline of a plate ideally becomes a solid filled or at least closed region that contour detection can latch onto.

Step seven — Find contours
Now the pipeline scans the morphologically closed binary image and extracts all the distinct connected regions — called contours. It uses RETR_EXTERNAL which means it only retrieves the outermost boundary of each region. This is important because without it, the algorithm would also find contours inside the plate — the individual characters, the holes in letters like O or B. Those inner contours are noise for this task. You only care about the outer boundary of the plate as a whole.
CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE just means the contour is stored compactly — instead of storing every single border pixel, it only stores the corner points. This saves memory and makes the subsequent geometric calculations faster.
The output at this point is a list of contours — potentially hundreds of them. Every region in the image that survived the edge and morphology steps shows up here. The plate might be in there, but so are road markings, shadows, car bumpers, signs, and all sorts of other rectangular or semi-rectangular structures in the scene.

Step eight — Filter candidates
This is the first round of elimination. For every contour found in the previous step, the pipeline applies a series of hard gates. Any contour that fails any gate is immediately discarded.
The gates are checking for the geometric properties of a license plate. First, aspect ratio — width divided by height must be between 2.0 and 6.5 roughly. A plate is a wide rectangle, so anything too square or too tall gets thrown out. Second, minimum size — the bounding box must be at least 40 pixels wide and 15 pixels tall. This eliminates tiny noise blobs. Third, minimum area — the bounding box area must be at least 1000 pixels. And fourth, fill ratio — the actual contour area divided by the bounding box area must be at least 0.35. This one is checking solidity. A plate is a mostly solid shape. An open or irregular contour — like a piece of tree branch or a curved shadow — would have a low fill ratio and gets filtered out here.
These gates are where most of the false positives get eliminated. After this step you're left with only the candidates that are geometrically plausible as license plates.

Step nine — Score candidates
The filter step ruled things out. The scoring step ranks what's left. For every candidate that survived the gates, the pipeline computes a score out of roughly 7 points.
Two points are awarded if the aspect ratio is in the sweet spot between 2.5 and 5.5 — tighter than the filter gate, rewarding more plate-like proportions. Two more points if the normalized width — width as a fraction of the full image width — falls between 8% and 60%. Two more points if the normalized height falls between 3% and 25%. And then the fill ratio is added as a continuous bonus on top of that.
The reason for scoring rather than just using stricter gates is flexibility. A gate is binary — pass or fail. A score is continuous — it lets candidates that tick more boxes float to the top, even if none of them are perfect. The candidate with the highest total score wins.